            <p align="left"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br>
              The European Union is unqiue in that European Community (EC) law 
              overrides the national laws of its member states. <br>
              <br>
              The <b>European Union</b> is made up of the following <b>25 Member 
              States</b>:<br>
              Austria, Belgium, Cyprus, Czech Republic, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, 
              France, Germany, Greece, Hungary, Ireland, Italy, Latvia, Lithuania, 
              Luxembourg, Malta, Poland, Portugal, Slovakia, Slovenia, Spain, 
              Sweden, The Netherlands and the United Kingdom (England, Wales, 
              Scotland &amp; Northern Ireland).<br>
              <br>
              The primary EC law is in the form of a series of <b>International 
              Treaties</b> (Rome, Maastrict, etc) agreed and signed by the Member 
              States. On the basis of these treaties secondary legislation, in 
              the form of Regulations, Directives, Decisions, Recommendations 
              and Opinions, is then made by the EU's institutions (European Parliament, 
              Council of Ministers, European Commission and the European Court 
              of Justice).<br>
              <br>
              EC legislation is published on a daily basis in the Official Journal.<br>
              </font></p>
            <p></p>
            <p align="left"><b><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">EC 
              Regulations</font></b><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"> 
              are binding on the Member States and have direct effect from the 
              date they enter into force, i.e. they are themselves part of national 
              law.<br>
              <br>
              <b>EC Directives</b> are also binding on the Member States but provide 
              scope for Member States to introduce their provisions into their 
              national legislation within a designated timeframe, i.e.they require 
              implementation by national legislation to become effective. States 
              that fail or refuse to implement directives as part of national 
              law can be fined by the European Court of Justice. <br>
              <b><br>
              EC Decisions</b> only affect the parties to whom they are addressed 
              (which can be individuals, corporations, or Member States). Decisions 
              are also used to define aspects of Directives that require more 
              technical detail and also to adopt international protocols.<br>
              <br>
              <b>EC Recommendations and Opinions</b> give guidance on certain 
              matters but are not binding on the Member States.<br>
              </font></p>
